text: "I want to see the story behind Apollo's son. Apollo's story is over. He was a good character; inspirational, powerful, prolific. Rocky's story is over. He's old, he's retired, he's done. Now I want to see what happens when that legend continues to thrive. I want to see what happens when legends are killed, I want to see what happens when legends are reborn. I want to see the new story behind Apollo's son."  Wow, whoever pitched this idea to Hollywood, I thank you so much. It's been a long time since we've got something with this much cinematic promise. Seriously, give that guy a raise or something. He's breathing new life into a stale industry.
author: Paul Lee

Era un donnadie que se abrió el solo las puertas del éxito.   No entiendo por qué la gran mayoría de las personas, no saben respetar y critican sin fundamentos. ¿Por qué? text: Ah, now picture this. Creed is a great fighter, trained by the best ever, Rocky Balboa, but he's a rich boy, he doesn't have the eye of a killer from the streets. Rocky had that naturally in the ring, but he doesn't know how to teach someone else to have the eye of a killer, he's too nice! He gets far but not yet to the top. He's still in his dads shadow. To get the eye of a snarling mad wrecking machine that just won't quit Rocky sets up a secret match behind closed doors. Creed enters the ring in a run down gym, there is no-one there. A door out of shot slams shut, Creed looks over, his face changes from anticipation to confused awe. We hear a man step into the ring, the camera pans over to where Creed is looking and reveals it to be Ivan Drago. Though much to Creeds disapproval, Rocky's plan to turn Creed from nothing more than a man living in his dad's shadow and wanting to prove that he is his dads equal into snarling mad wrecking machine that just won't quit works instantly. Now there is no stopping Creed from getting to the top and along the way, he learns to forgive Ivan which allows him to finally bury his demons.   Yeah it's corny but it just feels so Rocky like :)

text: In Britain, slavery continued to be practiced following the fall of Rome and sections of Hywel the Good's laws dealt with slaves in medieval Wales. The trade particularly picked up after the Viking invasions, with major markets at Chester and Bristol supplied by Danish, Mercian, and Welsh raiding of one another's borderlands. At the time of the Domesday Book, nearly 10% of the English population were slaves. Slavery in early medieval Europe was so common that the Roman Catholic Church repeatedly prohibited it — or at least the export of Christian slaves to non-Christian lands was prohibited at e.g. the Council of Koblenz (922), the Council of London (1102), and the Council of Armagh (1171). In 1452, Pope Nicholas V issued the papal bull Dum Diversas, granting the kings of Spain and Portugal the right to reduce any "Saracens (antiquated term referring to Muslims), pagans and any other unbelievers" to perpetual slavery, legitimizing the slave trade as a result of war. The approval of slavery under these conditions was reaffirmed and extended in his Romanus Pontifex bull of 1455. However, Pope Paul III forbade enslavement of the native Americans in 1537 in his papal bull Sublimus Dei. Dominican friars who arrived at the Spanish settlement at Santo Domingo strongly denounced the enslavement of the local native Americans. Along with other priests, they opposed their treatment as unjust and illegal in an audience with the Spanish king and in the subsequent royal commission.

text: I wrote this same idea on a boxing message board years ago. I'm glad somebody stole it and made it happen. But actually my idea was to make a series about Apollo Creed as a pre-quel as he came up the ranks and eventually met up with Rocky Balboa in "Rocky". But period pieces are expensive, so the writer went with the more practical, cost-effective route, I can't say I blame them.  With the thick mustache Michael B. Jordan actually favors Carl Weathers and got eyes like him when he is shadowboxing in the corner, like he could be his son. I hope it's good like "Rocky Balboa" was.

text: Wow, that took me off guard! I thought 'Creed' was going to be a prequel, about Apollo Creed's rise to fame before the events of 'Rocky', which is why I was surprised at how modern the setting looked. Not even the line "your daddy died in the ring" tipped me off since I thought it was a foreboding call-forward to Apollo's eventual fate, showing that he accepted it when he began. I wasn't expecting it to be a SEQUEL, and I CERTAINLY wasn't expecting Sylvester Stallone to show up to be junior's mentor. This feels like it really could be as awesome as 'Rocky Balboa' after all, rather than the shameless cash-in I was concerned it might be when I first heard about it.  Hey, I wonder if young Creed will ever get to fight Mason 'The Line' Dixon? That'd be neat.

text: How awful looking, instead of giving a unique voice to Apollo Creed or his descendant it looks like they tried to refit it back into the same Rocky story, thus creating black Rocky instead of an Apollo Creed Film. Gone is the Ali like banter of Creed, gone is the fact that his son would have been well off, instead we are greeted with the decaying urban landscape, gone is the fact he would have lots of advantages to getting into the boxing world, replaced by the underdog story and having to be trained by people not in the fighting world. No way the son of Apollo Creed grows up an outsider and an underdog. Just an attempt to return to tropes of the boxing genre instead of giving the film any new perspective. Coogler should be able to do better than this. (Granted maybe I'm wrong, its just a trailer, but my interest is non-existence).

text: Wow... this is like a "Boxing Cinematic Universe". This got me thinking... They could make boxing movie "crossovers"... In boxing movies, you always follow *one* protagonist. You see him go through his life's struggles, overcome obstacles, challenge himself and eventually win the big fight. In the meantime, his opponent is *always* portrayed as a "mean" tough guy with no relevant backstory. But what if the opponent *had* a backstory? Equally moving as the protagonist's? What if you make *TWO* separate boxing movies. Each about a different boxer's journey and prize fights... and in each of the fighters' solo movies, you would sometimes see small hints or cameos of the *other* fighter. Then, you would have them *both* meet in the ring in a *3rd* movie.  I personally think that would be awesome. It would give the final fight tremendous importance... (kind of like what Marvel does with its superheroes but in a *realistic* boxing world).

text: A lot of people are saying this film takes place in 2015. Now I happened to watch this trailer a lot and I found out a couple things. Apollo died in 1985. Now we can assume his wife was 1 or 2 months pregnant because they didn't tell anybody. Adonis says he never knew him. So obviously he was born after the death of Apollo. Rocky 6 was filmed in 2006  we know this because rocky still has his restaurant. Here's something intresting. In 1:36, you can clearly see Adonis wearing bred 11 highs. Bred 11s came out in 2012. So this film had to be set in 2012 or 2013. Rocky also looks older so we can assume that this film takes place in 2012 or 2013. Or Adonis had the bred 11s since release and the film was set in 2015. Hope this sheds some light to people

text: Alright, so if we assume the Rocky and "The Wire" universes are the same, how can this all take place.  Avon was a boxer growing up.  He was only arrested and could've been let out soon with good behavior and his lawyer pulling strings.  if u remember in Season 2 or 3, they started doing business in Philly, so it is plausible he has a safe spot in Philly and ended up working in a gym.  Now Wallace Creed said he didn't know his dad and had to fight his whole life.  So maybe it is plausible he grew up poor and became a lookout for heroin dealers.  So if we assume he never really died or just recovered from his head shot wound (lol), he could easily have joined the boxing gym that Tyrese from The Walking Dead opened up and learned how to box.

text: I'm a diehard fan of the Rocky series & have no idea what this movie will be about... The only thing I don't quiet understand about the series is, why does Apollo Creed's son feel like he has something to fight for, yet Rocky Balboa's son does not?  Of course they're 2 different people, but they're the sons of the 2 greatest fictional boxers of all time, so surely it has to be in the genes right? I mean it's like both son's were born into wealthiness, with the Creed family being much better off financially than the Balboa family, until Rocky took the torch away from Apollo that is, won it all, lost it all again, then got some of it back with the flourishing restaurant business. Robert never had the heart of a fighter, yet Adonis has, so it's as if Apollo Creed's son (whom I'm guessing never knew his father) can relate to Rocky (as a father figure) much more than Rocky's own son can relate to his own father. I know I'm just making assumptions... Guess I just have to watch the movie to know what it's all about.

text: This is the rocky follow up we needed. Rocky has been through a lot over the course of the 6 films. If we count the films chronology of events, he has been blind in 1 eye since the 2nd film, had a brain tumour from the 5th film, and has been through a lot since he was a simple boxer in 1. Now you have CREED, a film about someone who is trying to forge their own identity as a boxer while living in the shadow of his father, his mentor and their combined past. It's fitting that rocky hand over his legacy to the son of his greatest rival and friend. It's the passing of the torch to the next generation.

text: Well, there it is, Rocky is going to be succeeded by Creed......well, that will be their plan anyway. No film and no team of actors will ever be able to recreate the magic that the original Rocky film and cast gave to us all, not in a million years. This is a good film, but its not a 'great' film and certainly not one that people will be talking about 30 years from now. How I hope they don't kill Rocky off in a similar scenario to Mickey. Personally I wish they hadn't brought the illness of cancer into the movie, it spoilt it for me. I hope were all not going to be put through seeing Rocky passing away in a deeply sad way. I almost hope they leave it to our own imagination, but I feel they won't. Some heroes should never die.............and that's the beauty of movie making......................they don't have too.

text: This is an awesome movie. The Rocky legacy continues, but so does the Apollo Creed legacy when Apollo's son Adonis played by Michael B. Jordan seeks out Rocky to train him to fight, at first Rocky does not want anything to do with him trying to leave that life behind but he ends up warming up to the kid and becomes his trainer. Adonis goes by his mother's last name trying not to follow in his father's shadow but towards the end of the movie, he realizes that owning up to your heritage is not a bad thing. This is a great movie it has the feel and charm of the first movie and Sylvester Stallone is excellent as always and he is the only original that returns we find out that Paulie died and that Robert his son moved away. The only new major characters we meet is Adonis, Bianca played by Tessa Thompson and Pretty Ricky Conlan played by Tony Bellew who is Adonis's opponent. The acting is great, the story is great, the directing is great and the music is great. We also find out that Rocky has cancer and watching him get treatment and train Adonis in the hospital was awesome especially the part where he says that the nurse could go a couple of rounds. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is Cinematastic rating 5/5
